[1]
Date: Thu, 22 Jun 2006 15:02:05 -0400
From: Laurie Garrett<lgarrett@cfr.org>

I would point out that there are no major game parks or wildlife
preserves located along the flyway between southern Nigeria and
Zambia's Victoria Falls. The one major forest area -- the Tai Forest,
which spans portions of Cameroon, Gabon and Congo, is undergoing
major logging operations and deforestation. The massive forest
regions, rivers and lakes of the DRO Congo are no longer tourist
destinations, due to ongoing violence in the region. Northern Zambia
is consumed by the Copperbelt region, which involves large-scale
mining operaitons. So the first piece of territory to which migrating
birds heading south from Nigeria might make their way and be noticed
by international tourists, is in fact Livingston, or Victoria Falls.
If this is confirmed as H5N1, it is likely there are infected birds
along the flyway from Nigeria, but, for the reasons above, were not
noted by any outsiders.
If this turns out to be H5N1, it is virtually 100 percent guaranteed
the virus is in birds immediately across the Zambezi in Zimbabwe
where political repression and violence have brought tourism to a
virtual halt. Birds that carry the virus would no doubt appear soon
in South Africa and Madagascar, if the Zambia sightings turn out to be H5N1.
--
Laurie Garrett
Senior Fellow for Global Health
Council on Foreign Relations
58 E. 68th St.
NY, NY 10021
<lgarrett@cfr.org>
<http://www.lauriegarrett.com>
