Date: 22 Jun 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
[This 1st commentary was in response to the earlier posting
Undiagnosed die-off, wild birds - Zambia (Livingston):RFI
20060622.1726 - Mod.MPP]
A major wetlands and National Park complex were missed in this
analysis in the Luangwa Valley of eastern Zambia.
The Kafue National Park is the size of Wales and located on a direct
line between the headwaters of the Congo watershed and Victoria Falls
<http://www.go2africa.com/zambia/zambia-map.asp>
<http://www.zambiatourism.com/travel/nationalparks/kafue.htm>
Also, the Luangwa Valley in eastern Zambia is another natural
ecological corridor into the Zambezi valley from central Africa and
would be used by many species that might move between these areas.
North Luangwa National Park and South Luangwa national Park
<http://www.zambezi.co.uk/safari/zambia/luangwa.html>
<http://www.game-reserve.com/zambia_north_luangwa.html>

[This 2nd commentary was in response to the comment contained in [1]
above. - Mod.MPP]
There is an error in the [above comment] regarding the supposed
absence of any National Parks or major game reserves between southern
Nigeria and Victoria Falls on the Zambezi River.
The Kafue National Park (22 400 sq km) in central Zambia is located
on the direct line drawn between southern Nigeria, the headwaters of
the Congo watershed, and Victoria Falls. The Kafue Flats marshes and
seasonal wetlands cover an area of approximately 6500 sq km in the
central region of the park. The area serves as an important regional
tourist destination and wildlife research area.
<http://www.go2africa.com/zambia/zambia-map.asp>
According to the World Wildlife Fund, the Kafue Flats ecosystem is
situated along major migration routes that carry birds migrating from
the Arctic as well as other areas of Africa. A total of more than
470 species of birds have been recorded in the area, and the Kafue
Flats are the home of the Kafue lechwe, an endemic species of wetland
antelope found nowhere else in Africa.
<http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/where_we_work/africa/where/zambia/kafue/species/index.cfm>
<http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/where_we_work/africa/where/zambia/kafue/species/lechwe/index.cfm>
--
Joe Dudley
Chief Scientist, Biosecurity & Bioinformatics
